						               													<description>As can be read on the Ravensburger homepage, the history of Punta is connected to Memory: In 1957, Carlit, the publisher of Punta, refused an offer from Heinrich and Josephine Hurter to issue their &amp;quot;Memory-Game&amp;quot; by referring to a &amp;quot;similar&amp;quot; game already in their program, Punta!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Today's Punta rules contain 3 possible ways to play Punta, but I don't know, if the first editions had only the version, which is indeed similar to Memory.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Common to all 3 sub-games is, that all 60 cards are evenly dealt to the players, which lay them on the table. The player who can turn all his cards first, is the winner.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;As in Memory, players can choose 2 cards to look at, but they can only choose their own cards and the revealed cards must match with the throw of the 2-4 dice (1-2 normal dice and 1-2 colour dice depending on the selected sub-game). &amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
